With the aim of exploring its feasibility as a useful bio-marker for living cells imaging, HeLa cells were incubated with sulfur dots under physiological conditions. The laser with an excitation wavelength of 405 nm was applied and it is clear that the carcinoma cells demonstrated striking blue fluorescence owing to the intense emission from sulfur dots, indicating that quantities of nanoparticles have been internalized into the cells (Fig. 7
                     ). The intracellular distributions of sulfur dots in K562 cells were also monitored via confocal laser scanning microscopy images (Fig. 7). Due to the incorporation of mercury ions at the concentration of 5 μM for 30 min, the blue luminescence was substantially reduced throughout the cell cytoplasm and the higher concentration of mercury ions would lead to quenching effect within the cells. The results clearly showed that sulfur dots could not only be applied for mercury sensing in aqueous solution or buffer environment, but also provide the possibility for real-time monitoring of Hg2+ against the interferences of biological substances (Fig. 8
                     ).
